elations with itstenants and neighbours, with the king and the central government. Chapters are also devoted to the monks' religious, cultural and intellectual life, to their writings, book collection and archives. Appendices focus on the mid-thirteenth century accounts which give a unique and detailed picture of the organisation and economy of St Edmunds' estates in West Suffolk, and on the abbey's watermills and windmills. Dr ANTONIA GRANSDEN is former Reader atthe University of Nottingham.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAbbeyszEnglandzBury St. EdmundsxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aAbbeyszEnglandzBury St. EdmundsxHistory. 0aAbbotszEnglandzBury St. Edmunds. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAbbey administration.  aMedieval England.  aMonastic life.  aReligious and cultural life.  aSt. Edmund's Abbey.  aThirteenth century.  aWest Suffolk.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184615555040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846155550423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846155550/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles